Anonymous Tue 08 May 2018 05:20:40 No.15634770 Report
Quoted By: >>15635698 >>15643109
>>15634437
That I doubt, not at least with so much manual adjustment that it wouldn't be anywhere close to the original asset file.
The software for their pipelines at places like Pixar and Disney are highly modified in house for optimization both for their workflow and more importantly their hardware (quadros and other uber expensive components) and various custom coded effects and other things they want for their films (Like for pixar OpenSubDiv, which is now open source and what they used for making footprints in snow without stupid high poly counts for Brave, and Disney animation their fur renderer for zootopia) along with their rigs dependent on stuff injected with custom code to deform right (Not 100% sure on that last one, but I'm pretty positive how they interact with a rig at least is custom for making it easier on the animators.)
For someone to somehow run off with the model completely intact and do animation like that, they'd need to probably jack a workstation with their propriety software on it and somehow remote connect it to their render farm (If that's not a closed LAN I'd be surprised) because there's no home machine in the world that can render the hair out like it was in the movie.
That model's probably something from scratch using a butt load of reference to get it down as closely as they can for their 3D suite of choice.
(Here's a good article on how they went about doing the fur: https://www.fxguide.com/featured/the-fur-reaching-tech-of-zootopia/)

No that's pretty much the opposite of how it works.

When you could die at any moment you have no time to be picky so you fuck as much as possible with anyone you can find for the slim chance of leaving behind your genes.
This is called r-selection.
Rabbits are very extreme r-selectors and as such don't stick around for their mate or even their children.

On the other hand when you have the power to defend yourself or are just not likely to be killed, you have time to be picky, stick around and have sex for extended periods of time.
This is called K-selection.
Pretty much all apex predators are K-selectors, humans probably being one of the most extreme examples.

>Today there was a frenzy of fish and would be consumers of fish somewhat close to the shore, or at least closer to the shore than I've ever seen one, close enough that I had to back up a bit 'cause I was worried I might scare some of the birds off.
>After the aerobatics show died down, the tide also came down, leaving a fish or two that for one reason or another hadn't made it back into the water.
>Usually I throw them back in, in the hopes I might see something try and grab it mid air as it flies back towards the water.
>This has only happened twice the month or two I've been here, but I remain hopeful anyway.
>I do this for the first fish and, not today it seems.
>The other one, wait...
>It's farther away and it's still rather dark at the moment, but it looks rather large for any fish I've seen swim into here.
>Getting closer, it looks more like a shark, but, with arms?
>Looking as though it was longer in length than I was tall, there's no way I'm throwing this into anything.
